Context¶

To minimize loss from the banks perspective, the bank needs a decision rule regarding whom to approve the loan and whom not to. An applicants demographic and socio-economic profiles are considered by loan managers before a decision is taken regarding his/her loan application. In this dataset, each entry represents a person who takes credit from a bank. Each person is classified as a good or bad credit risk according to the set of attributes.

Objective¶

The objective is to build a predictive model on this data to help the bank decide on whether to approve a loan to a prospective applicant.

Dataset¶

  • Age (Numeric: Age in years)
  • Sex (Categories: male, female)
  • Job (Categories: unskilled and non-resident, unskilled and resident, skilled, highly skilled)
  • Housing (Categories: own, rent, or free)
  • Saving accounts (Categories: little, moderate, quite rich, rich)
  • Checking account (Categories: little, moderate, rich)
  • Credit amount (Numeric: Amount of credit in DM - Deutsche Mark)
  • Duration (Numeric: Duration for which the credit is given in months)
  • Purpose (Categories: car, furniture/equipment,radio/TV, domestic appliances, repairs, education, business, vacation/others)
  • Risk (0 - Person is not at risk, 1 - Person is at risk(defaulter))

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

def countPlot(feature):
    val_count = (data[feature].value_counts() / data[feature].count()) * 100
    for i in range(len(val_count)):
        print(val_count.index[i], ":", np.round(val_count[i], 2), "%")
    sns.set({"figure.figsize": (10, 5)})
    sns.countplot(x=feature, data=data)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)

# percentage of default(1) or not default(0) w.r.t each category
def percentage_0_1(feature):
    val_count = data[feature].value_counts()

    for i in range(len(val_count)):

        print(
            "-----------Out of all ",
            val_count.index[i],
            " (",
            val_count[i],
            ")-----------",
        )

        d1 = len(
            data[(data[val_count.name] == val_count.index[i]) & (data["Risk"] == 1)]
        )
        not_d1 = len(
            data[(data[val_count.name] == val_count.index[i]) & (data["Risk"] == 0)]
        )

        d2 = np.round((d1 / val_count[i]) * 100, 2)
        not_d2 = np.round((not_d1 / val_count[i]) * 100, 2)
        print(d2, "% ", val_count.index[i], " -----------default")
        print(not_d2, "% ", val_count.index[i], " -----------not default\n")

Overall Insights¶

  • class distribution in the target variable is imbalanced , 70% observations for non-defaulters and 30% observations for defaulters
  • The distribution of age is right-skewed, mean=35.5, median=33
    • more chances to default--younger customers compare to elder customers
    • defaulters who have housing=free, job=higly_skilled are elder than the non-defaulter
    • if purpose=business or domestic appliance then defaulters are mostly elder than non-defaulters
  • The distribution of the credit amount is also right-skewed, mean=3271, median=2319
    • more chances to default--high credit amount compare to low credit amount customers
    • defaulters will have low credit amount when checking account=rich compare to non-defaulters
  • The distribution of the duration for which the credit is given is right-skewed, mean=21, median=18
    • more chances to default--high duration compare to customers having low duration
  • There are 69% male customers and 31% female customers
    • more chance to default-- female compare to male customers
  • 63% skilled category, 22% unskilled, 15% highly skilled category
    • more chances to default-- highly skilled compare to others
    • most chance to default-- highly skilled and purpose=vacation/others
  • 71% own house, 18% rented house, 11% free housing
    • more chances to default-- persons who have rent/free housing compare to others
    • less chance to default--samples having housing=rent, checking account=little and saving account!=little. i.e., 5 samples belong to that combination and all having risk=0
  • 89% customers little or moderate savings account, 11% customers rich/quite-rich savings account
  • 94% customers little or moderate checking account, 6% customers rich checking account
    • more chances to default-- persons with little checking account compare to moderate and rich checking accounts
    • least chances to default-- person having little checking account and rich/quite-rich saving account
    • least chance to default-- persons having little checking account, rich saving account and own the house i.e., there are total 4 samples in the dataset that have little+rich+own and all have risk=0
    • least chances to default-- person having rich checking account and any saving account except little
  • most customers take credit for luxury items (i.e., car=33.7%, radio=28%, furniture=18.1%) less customers take credit for business(9.7%), education(5.9%) ,vacation-others(1.2%) etc
    • more chance to default-- persons who have taken credit for vacation-others, education or for repairs compare to other categories
    • less chance to default-- persons who have taken credit for radio/TV compare to other categories

Model Building¶

Model evaluation criterion¶

Model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  1. Predicting a customer is not going to default but in reality the customer will default - Loss of resources
  2. Predicting a customer is going to default but in reality the customer will not default - Loss of opportunity

Which Loss is greater ?¶

  • Loss of resources will be the greater loss as the bank will be losing their resources i.e., profit/interest 10,000 on loan 100,000: if FP-> loss 10,000 profit but if FN-> loss 100,000 resources

How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Negatives ?¶

  • Company would want to reduce false negatives, this can be done by maximizing the Recall. Greater the recall lesser the chances of false negatives.

As this is the exercise of logistic regression so we have selected logistic regression for our classifier, now need to select the values for their parameters¶

Coefficient interpretations¶

  • Coefficients of Credit amount, Duration and some categorical levels of Purpose are positive, an increase in values of these variables (or variable=1) will lead to an increase in chances of a customer being a defaulter.
  • Coefficients of Age, Sex_male, Housing, Saving accounts, checking accounts ,job and some categorical levels of Purpose are negative, an increase in values of these variables (or variable=1) will lead to a decrease in chances of a customer being a defaulter.

Converting coefficients(log odds_ratio) to odds_ratio¶

  • The coefficients of the logistic regression model are in terms of log(odds_ratio), to find the odds_ratio we have to take the exponential of the coefficients.
  • b=log(odds_ratio), and b is any coefficient
  • Therefore, odds_ratio = exp(b)
  • The percentage change in odds is given as odds = (exp(b) - 1) * 100
In [117]:
# converting log_odds_ratio to odds_ratio

odds_ratio = np.exp(log_odds_ratio)

# finding the percentage change
perc_change_odds = (odds_ratio - 1) * 100

Coefficient interpretations:¶

  • Credit Amount: 11.53% increase in odds of a customer being a defaulter by increasing the credit amount by one unit(2970 DM), holding all other features constant at certain value.

  • Duration: 18.67% increase in odds of a customer being a defaulter by increasing the duration by one unit(11.9 months), holding all other features constant at certain value.

  • Sex_male: odds of a male customer being a defaulter is 16.49% lesser than the female customer, holding all other features constant at certain value.

  • Housing: odds of a customer who has own house being a defaulter is 19.97% lesser than the customers who has free house. And odds of a customer who has rented house being a defaulter is 0.44% lesser than the customers who has free house.[keeping housing_free as reference] Holding all other features constant at certain value.

Just consider credit_amount (coef or odds% )¶

  • In case of unscaled data: 0.000047/0.0047%
    • It seems that this coefficient has the very least impact on the odds of being a defaulter
    • Yes, of course, we can measure the strength of the impact on odds by the coefficient. But a smaller coefficient can be due to both reasons, one is in lesser relation with the target column and the second is due to unscaled data w.r.t to other variables. So when a variable has larger values compared to other variables then during training smaller coefficient can be, to avoid bias in the model towards a particular variable(just due to the reason of larger values).
    • 0.0047% increase in odds of belonging to default, when credit amount increased by one unit(1 DM).
    • In another sense, if you will consider this dataset then you will get the idea that values in the credit amount are not increasing or decreasing by 1 DM. But in the case of a categorical variable, with the change of the variable's value, direct category change
  • In case of scaled data: 0.1/11.53%
    • 11.5% increase in odds of belonging to default, when credit amount increase by one unit(2970DM)
    • Easy to compare the impact of this variable(coefficients) with other variables when data is scaled.

Checking model's performance¶

In [124]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn

def model_performance_classification_sklearn_with_threshold(model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics, based on the threshold specified, to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred_prob = model.predict_proba(predictors)[:, 1]
    pred =binarize(pred_prob.reshape(len(pred_prob), 1), threshold=threshold)
    
    
    
    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

def plot_precision_recall_vs_threshold(precisions, recalls, thresholds):
    plt.title('Precision_Recall Curve')
    sns.lineplot(thresholds, precisions[:-1],label='precisions');
    sns.lineplot(thresholds, recalls[:-1],label='recalls');
    plt.xlabel('Threshold')
    plt.legend();

Recommendations¶

  • From our logistic regression model we identified that Duration is significant predictor of a customer being a defaulter.
  • back should target the customers who has their own houses
  • Bank should target more male customers as they have lesser odds of defaulting.
  • We saw in our analysis that customers with a little or moderate amount in saving or checking accounts are more likely to default. The bank can be more strict with its rules or interest rates to compensate for the risk.
  • We saw that customers who have rented or free housing are more likely to default. The bank should keep more details about such customers like hometown addresses, etc. to be able to track them.
  • Our analysis showed that younger customers are slightly more likely to default. The bank can alter its policies to deal with this.
